material.mattext: Within which interval of rating would you expect to find the largest number of shows?

Incorrect. When answering this question, it will be useful to remember that: 25% of the data fall below Q1 (11), 25% of the data fall between Q1 (11) and M (14), 25% of the data fall between M (14) and Q3 (20), and 25% of the data fall above Q3 (20). Note that 10 is below the first quartile, so we expect less than 25% of the shows to have a rating in that interval.

Correct. Note that 10 is below Q1, and 15 is above the M, so we expect more than 25% of the shows to have ratings in that interval. Using a similar reasoning, in all the other intervals we would expect to see LESS than 25% of the shows.

Incorrect. When answering this question, it will be useful to remember that: 25% of the data fall below Q1 (11), 25% of the data fall between Q1 (11) and M (14), 25% of the data fall between M (14) and Q3 (20), and 25% of the data fall above Q3 (20). Note that 15 is above the median, and 20 is Q3, so we expect less than 25% of the shows to have a rating in that interval.

Incorrect. When answering this question, it will be useful to remember that: 25% of the data fall below Q1 (11), 25% of the data fall between Q1 (11) and M (14), 25% of the data fall between M (14) and Q3 (20), and 25% of the data fall above Q3 (20). Note that 20 is Q3, but 25 is below the largest observation, so we expect less than 25% of the shows to have a rating in that interval.

Incorrect. Intervals of equal LENGTH do not necessarily have the same number of observations fall in them. When answering this question, it will be useful to remember that: 25% of the data fall below Q1 (11), 25% of the data fall between Q1 (11) and M (14), 25% of the data fall between M (14) and Q3 (20), and 25% of the data fall above Q3 (20).
